.com/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-1002284517|title=Guettel, Adam {{!}} Grove Music|language=en|doi=10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.A2284517|access-date=April 7, 2018|year=2015|last1=Warfield|first1=Scott}}</ref> humorist [[Greg Daniels]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://exeter.edu/news/exeter-explorations-2014-bringing-new-perspectives-back-campus|title=Exeter Explorations: Bringing New Perspectives Back to Campus|work=Phillips Exeter Academy|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref> mathematicians [[Shinichi Mochizuki]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://projectwordsworth.com/the-paradox-of-the-proof/|title=The Paradox of the Proof|date=May 5, 2013|work=Project Wordsworth|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> [[David Mumford]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shawprize.org/en/shaw.php?tmp=3&twoid=51&threeid=63&fourid=107&fiveid=24|title=The Shaw Prize \u2013 Top prizes for astronomy, life science and mathematics|website=www.shawprize.org|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> and [[Lloyd Shapley]], winner of the 2012 Nobel Prize in economics;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.informs.org/Explore/History-of-O.R.-Excellence/Biographical-Profiles/Shapley-Lloyd-S.|title=Shapley, Lloyd S.|last=INFORMS|website=INFORMS|language=en-US|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> economist [[Paul Romer]], winner of the 2018 Nobel Prize in economics,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2018/10/08/nobel-prize-economics-william-nordhaus-paul-romer-mit-phillips-exeter-academy/|title=2 Researchers With MIT Ties Win Nobel Prize for Economics|date=October 8, 2018|access-date=October 8, 2018|language=en}}</ref> computer scientist [[Adam D'Angelo]] (co-founder of [[Quora]]);<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/adam-dangelo/|title=Adam D'Angelo|work=Forbes|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref> and philosopher and evolutionary biologist [[Daniel Dennett]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newphilosopher.com/articles/the-secret-of-consciousness-with-daniel-c-dennett/|title=The secret of consciousness, with Daniel C. Dennett {{!}} New Philosopher|website=www.newphilosopher.com|language=en|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Other academic programs==\n\n===Summer school===\nEach summer, Phillips Exeter hosts over 780 students from various schools for a five-week program of academic study.  The summer program accommodates a diverse student body typically derived from over 40 different states and 45 foreign countries.<ref>{{cite web| last=The Trustees of Phillips Exeter Academy| title=Phillips Exeter Academy {{!}} Summer School| url=http://www.exeter.edu/summer_programs/7324.aspx| accessdate=January 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\nExeter's summer school is divided into two programs of study: Upper School, which offers a wide variety of classes to students currently enrolled in high school who are entering grades ten through 12 as well as serving postgraduates; and Access Exeter, a program for students entering grades eight and nine, which offers accelerated study in the arts, sciences and writing as well as serving as an introduction to the school itself. Access Exeter curriculum consists of six academic clusters; each cluster consists of three courses organized around a focused central theme. Some of Exeter's summer school programs also give students the opportunity to experience studies outside of Exeter's campus environment, including interactions with other top schools and students, experience with Washington D.C., and travel abroad.<ref>{{cite web|last=The Trustees of Phillips Exeter Academy|title=Phillips Exeter Academy {{!}} Academic Programs|url=http://www.exeter.edu/summer_programs/7324_7416.aspx|accessdate=January 7, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116051529/http://www.exeter.edu/summer_programs/7324_7416.aspx|archivedate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Workshops===\nThe academy offers a number of workshops and conferences for secondary school educators. These include the Exeter Math Institute; the Exeter Humanities Institute; the Math, Science and Technology Conference; the Exeter Astronomy Conference; and the Shakespeare Conference.<ref>{{cite web|title=Summer Programs |url=http://www.exeter.edu/summer_programs/88.aspx |accessdate=November 12, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220074005/http://www.exeter.edu/summer_programs/88.aspx |archivedate=December 20, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe \"On Beyond Exeter\" program offers one-week seminars for alumni. Most courses are held at the academy, but some meet in the locations central to the course's topic.\n\n===Historical endeavors===\nIn 1952, Exeter, [[Phillips Academy|Andover]], [[Lawrenceville School|Lawrenceville]], [[Harvard University|Harvard]], [[Princeton University|Princeton]] and [[Yale University|Yale]] published the study ''General Education in School and College: A Committee Report''. The report recommended examinations that would place students after admission to college. This program evolved into the [[Advanced Placement Program]].<ref>{{cite web| title = The Liberal Arts in School and College| author=Stanley N. Katz| url=http://chronicle.com/free/v52/i27/27b04601.htm|website=Chronicle.com| accessdate = November 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title = A Brief History of the Advanced Placement Program| url = http://www.collegeboard.com/prod_downloads/about/news_info/ap/ap_history_english.pdf| website = Collegeboard.com| accessdate = November 12, 2017| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090205075824/http://www.collegeboard.com/prod_downloads/about/news_info/ap/ap_history_english.pdf| archive-date = February 5, 2009| url-status = dead| df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1965 Exeter became the second charter member (after [[Phillips Academy|Andover]]) of the [[School Year Abroad]] program.<ref>{{cite web| title = A Brief History: Where did we come from?| url = http://www.sya.org/pages/sitepage.cfm?id=22&pagename=A%20Brief%20History%20of%20SYA| website = Sya.org| accessdate = November 12, 2017| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090728204959/http://www.sya.org/pages/sitepage.cfm?id=22&pagename=A%20Brief%20History%20of%20SYA| archivedate = July 28, 2009| df = mdy-all}}</ref> The program allows students to reside and study a foreign language abroad.\n\n==In popular culture==\n{{See also|List of Phillips Exeter Academy people#In fiction}}\n\nSeveral works are based on Exeter and portray the lives of its students. Many are written by alumni who disguise Exeter's name, but not its character, such as [[John Knowles]] and his novel ''[[A Separate Peace]].''\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Schools}}\n*[[Exeter point]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{citation |editor=[[Paul Monroe]] |via=HathiTrust |title= Cyclopedia of Education |publisher=Macmillan |location=New York |year=1913 |chapter=Phillips Academy, Exeter, N.H. |volume=4 |hdl=2027/uc2.ark:/13960/t1vd73q7n }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Americana Poster|Phillips (Exeter) Academy}}\n* [http://www.exeter.edu/ Phillips Exeter Academy]\n* [http://www.exetercrew.com/ Phillips Exeter Academy Crew]\n* [https://archive.is/20130209041828/http://www.webofstories.com/people/donald.hall/13 Donald Hall talking about Phillips Exeter Academy] (video)\n{{Phillips Exeter Academy}}\n\n{{Eight Schools Association}}\n{{The Ten Schools Admissions Organization}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Phillips Exeter Academy]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Private high schools in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Preparatory schools in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 1780s]]\n[[Category:1781 establishments in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Co-educational boarding schools]]\n[[Category:Schools in Rockingham County, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Exeter, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Six Schools League]]\n[[Category:Phillips family (New England)]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Phillips Academy Andover}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Coord|42|58|48|N|70|57|04|W|type:edu|display=title}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name = Phillips Exeter Academy\n| image = Phillips Exeter Academy Seal.png\n| caption = \n| motto = {{lang-la|Non Sibi}} <br />(Not for Oneself)<br />{{lang-la|Finis Origine Pendet}} <br />(The End Depends Upon the Beginning)<br />{{lang-gr|\u03a7\u03ac\u03c1\u03b9\u03c4\u03b9 \u0398\u03b5\u03bf\u1fe6}} <br />(By the Grace of God)\n| location = 20 Main Street\n| city = [[Exeter, New Hampshire|Exeter]]\n| state = [[New Hampshire]]\n| zipcode = 03833\n| country = USA\n| type = [[Private school|Independent]], [[Day school|day]] & [[boarding school|boarding]]\n| established = 1781\n| founder = [[John Phillips (educator)|John Phillips]]<br>Elizabeth Phillips{{refn|group=nb|Elizabeth Phillips was recognized as co-founder of Phillips Exeter alongside her husband John in 2018.<ref>{{Citation\n | last = Brandes\n | first = Anne\n | author-link =\n | last2 = Little\n | first2 = Ginny\n | title = Academy Center Honors Female Co-Founders\n | publisher = [[The Exonian]]\n | date = September 13, 2018}}</ref>}}\n| ceeb = 300185\n| grades = [[Ninth grade#United States|9]]\u2013[[Twelfth grade#United States|12]]\n| head = [[William Rawson (educator)|William K. Rawson]]<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://exeter.edu/news/bill-rawson-71-named-principal-phillips-exeter-academy| last1=Muldoon| first1=Brian| title=Bill Rawson '71 named principal at Phillips Exeter Academy| work=Phillips Exeter Academy| date=Jan 24, 2019| access-date=January 25, 2019}}</ref>\n| faculty = 217\n| gender = [[Coeducational]]\n| enrollment = 1,096 total<br />865 boarding<br/>214 day\n| class = 12 students\n| ratio = 5:1\n| athletics = 22 Interscholastic sports<br />62 Interscholastic teams\n| conference = [[NEPSAC]] <br> [[Six Schools League|SSL]]\n| team_name = Big Red\n| rival = [[Phillips Academy, Andover]]\n| accreditation = [[National Association of Independent Schools|NAIS]] <br> TABS\n| newspaper = [[The Exonian]]\n| yearbook = PEAN\n| budget = $107 million ''(2017-2018)''<ref name=Facts>{{Cite web| url=https://www.exeter.edu/sites/default/files/documents/Facts-2018.pdf| title=FACTS: 2018-2019| publisher=Phillips Exeter Academy| access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref>\n| affiliations = [[Eight Schools Association]] <br> [[G20 Schools]] <br> Ten Schools Admissions Organization\n| alumni = Exonians\n| head_name = [[List of Phillips Exeter Academy Principals|Principal]]\n| campus = [[Town]]<br />132 buildings\n| campus_size = {{convert|673|acre|km2}}\n| colors = Maroon and Grey <br> {{Color box|#911236|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|grey|border=darkgray}}\n| homepage = {{URL|www.exeter.edu}}\n| endowment = $1.3 billion ''(as of June 2018)''<ref>{{cite web |title=Financial Report 2018|website=Phillips Exeter Academy|url=https://www.exeter.edu/sites/default/files/documents/PEA-Financial-Report-FY2018.pdf}}</ref>\n| annual tuition = $55,402 (boarding) <br>\n$43,272 (day)<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.exeter.edu/admissions-and-financial-aid/tuition-financial-aid | title= Phillips Exeter Academy Tuition & Fees 2019\u20132020 | accessdate= August 26, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Phillips Exeter Academy''' (often called '''Exeter''' or '''PEA''') is a highly selective, coeducational [[independent school]] for boarding and day students in grades 9 through 12, and offers a secondary postgraduate program. Located in [[Exeter, New Hampshire]], it is one of the oldest secondary schools in the United States. Its history, influence, wealth, and academic reputation have made it one of the most elite boarding schools in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/most-elite-boarding-schools-in-america-2016-2|title=The 50 most elite boarding schools in America|last=Loudenback|first=Emmie Martin, Tanza|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.niche.com/k12/search/best-boarding-high-schools/|title=2020 Best Boarding High Schools in America|website=Niche|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/ed/2017/05/03/526769862/elite-prep-schools-experiment-with-all-gender-dorms|title=Elite Prep Schools Experiment With 'All-Gender' Dorms|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|date=1996|title=The Status of African Americans at the Nation's Most Prestigious Boarding Schools|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/2962808|journal=The Journal of Blacks in Higher Education|issue=14|pages=26\u201328|doi=10.2307/2962808|issn=1077-3711}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/mark-zuckerberg-attended-the-most-elite-boarding-school-in-america/articleshow/51082462.cms|title=Mark Zuckerberg attended the most elite boarding school in America|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Fabrikant|first=Geraldine|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/26/business/26prep.html|title=At Elite Prep Schools, College-Size Endowments|date=2008-01-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetelegraph.com/technology/businessinsider/article/Booths-Full-Of-Booze-Electric-Mermaids-And-6006613.php|title=What it's like to attend Phillips Exeter Academy, one of the most elite boarding schools in America|last=Robinson|first=Melia|last2=By|first2=Provided|date=2019-08-09|website=The Telegraph|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=JOURNAL|first=Suein HwangStaff Reporter of THE WALL STREET|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB112060492484077856|title=Boarding Schools Face New Hurdle: Mom and Dad|date=2005-07-07|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-03-24|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660|quote=\"Some of the most famous boarding schools, such as the Phillips Academy Andover in Massachusetts and Phillips Exeter Academy in New Hampshire...\"}}</ref>\n\nExeter is based on the [[Harkness table|Harkness education]] system, a conference format of student interaction with minimal teacher involvement. It has the largest endowment of any New England boarding school, which as of 2018 was valued at $1.3 billion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/most-famous-phillips-exeter-alumni-2016-2|title=Mark Zuckerberg attended the most elite boarding school in America|work=Business Insider|access-date=April 10, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Facts\" /> On January 25, 2019, William K. Rawson was appointed by the academy's trustees as the 16th Principal Instructor. He is the 4th alumnus of Exeter to serve as Principal Instructor, after [[Gideon Lane Soule]] (1838\u20131873), [[Harlan Amen]] (1895\u20131913), and [[William Saltonstall]] (1946\u20131963).\n\nPhillips Exeter Academy has educated several generations of the New England establishment and prominent American politicians, but has introduced many programs to diversify the student population, including need-blind admission. In 2018, over 45% of students received financial aid from grants totaling over $22 million. The school has been historically highly selective, with an acceptance rate of 15% for the 2019\u20132020 school year, and approximately 30% of graduates attend an [[Ivy League]] university, [[Stanford University]], or the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://theexonian.com/ |title=PEA Accepts 15 Percent of Applicants |last=Akil |first=Moksha |date=March 21, 2019 |work=The Exonian |access-date= |last2=Yeung |first2=Felix}}</ref><ref name=matriculations>{{cite web |url=https://www.exeter.edu/sites/default/files/documents/college_matriculation.pdf |title=College Matriculation for Classes 2016-2018  |website=exeter.edu |accessdate=August 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nManagement of the school's financial and physical resources is overseen by trustees drawn from alumni. Day-to-day operations are headed by a principal, who is appointed by the trustees. The faculty of the school are responsible for governing matters relating to student life, both in and out of the classroom.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.exeter.edu/governance/7856.aspx | work=Phillips Exeter Academy | title=Governance at Exeter | accessdate=February 23, 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130224110320/http://www.exeter.edu/governance/7856.aspx | archivedate=February 24, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe school's first enrolled class counted 56 boys;<ref name=Crosbie-1923>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ywHhswEACAAJ |title=The Phillips Exeter Academy; A History by Laurence M. Crosbie |date=1923 |publisher=The Academy |language=en}}</ref> in 1970, when the decision was made to implement co-education, there were 700 boys.<ref name=Crimson-Coed>{{cite news| url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1970/2/28/phillips-exeter-to-go-coed-pthe/ | work=The Harvard Crimson | title=Phillips Exeter to Go Coed | date=February 28, 1970 | accessdate=February 23, 2013}}</ref> The 2018 academic year saw enrollment at 1,096 students, with 883 boarding students and 213 day students.<ref name=Facts/> The students comprise roughly equal numbers of males and females, who are housed in 25 single-sex and two mixed-sex dormitories. Each residence is supervised by a dormitory head selected from the faculty.\n\n==History==\n{{See also|List of Phillips Exeter Academy principals}}\n\n===Origins===\n[[File:Portrait of John Phillips.jpeg|thumb|left|[[John Phillips (educator)|John Phillips]], the founder of Phillips Exeter Academy]]\n[[File:Original Phillips Exeter Academy Building.jpg|thumb|First Academy Building c. 1910, where the school opened in 1783]]\nPhillips Exeter Academy was established in Exeter, New Hampshire in 1781 by Elizabeth and [[John Phillips (educator)|John Phillips]]. John Phillips had made his fortune as a merchant and banker before going into public service, and financially supported his nephew [[Samuel Phillips, Jr.]] in founding his own school, [[Phillips Academy]], in [[Andover, Massachusetts]], three years earlier. As a result of this family relationship, the two schools share a rivalry.<ref name=Echols>{{Cite journal | last=Echols | first=Edward | title=The Phillips Exeter Academy, A Pictorial History | publisher=Exeter Press | year=1970| page=49 | ref=harv }}</ref> The school that Phillips founded at Exeter was to educate students under a [[Calvinist]] religious framework. However, like his nephew who founded Andover, Phillips stipulated in the school's founding charter that it would \"ever be equally open to youth of requisite qualifications from every quarter.\"<ref name=Crosbie-1923 />\n\nPhillips had previously been married to Sarah Gilman, wealthy widow of Phillips' cousin, merchant Nathaniel Gilman,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.exeter.edu/documents/Exeter_Bulletin/summer_05/BehindEverySuccessfulMan.pdf| title=Behind Every Successful Man| last=Brown| first=Connie| publisher=The Exeter Bulletin| date=Summer 2005| accessdate=August 27, 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405142954/http://www.exeter.edu/documents/Exeter_Bulletin/summer_05/BehindEverySuccessfulMan.pdf| archivedate=April 5, 2012| df=mdy-all}}</ref> whose large fortune, bequeathed to Phillips, enabled him to endow the academy.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/phillipsexeterac00bell|title=Phillips Exeter Academy in New Hampshire, Charles Henry Bell, William B. Morrill, Exeter, N.H., 1883|publisher=W. B. Morrill, printer|year=1883|last1=Bell |first1=Charles Henry }}</ref> The Gilman family also donated to the academy much of the land on which it stands, including the initial 1793 grant by [[Governor of New Hampshire|New Hampshire Governor]] [[John Taylor Gilman]] of the Yard, the oldest part of campus; the academy's first class in 1783 included seven Gilmans.<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NVNm_97RrcwC&pg=PA163 |title=New Hampshire: A Guide to the Granite State, Federal Writers Project, Houghton Mifflin Company, Boston, 1938| isbn=9781603540285| year=1938}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6UZAAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA5 |title=General Catalogue of Officers and Students, 1783\u20131903, The Phillips Exeter Academy, News-Letter Press, Exeter, 1903|year=1903|last1=Academy |first1=Phillips Exeter }}</ref> In 1814, [[Nicholas Gilman]], signer of the [[United States Constitution|U.S. Constitution]], left $1,000 to Exeter to teach \"sacred music.\"<ref name=Trustees>{{cite web|last=The trustees of Phillips Exeter Academy |title=Phillips Exeter Academy {{!}} Academy Chronology |url=https://www.exeter.edu/about-us/academy-chronology |accessdate=July 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe academy's first schoolhouse, the First Academy Building, was built on a site on Tan Lane in 1783, and today stands not far from its original location. The building was dedicated on February 20, 1783, the same day that the school's first Preceptor, [[William Woodbridge (educator)|William Woodbridge]], was chosen by John Phillips.<ref name=Crosbie-1923 />\n\nExeter's ''Deed of Gift,'' written by John Phillips at the founding of the school, states that Exeter's mission is to instill in its students both goodness and knowledge:\n{{quote|\"Above all, it is expected that the attention of instructors to the disposition of the minds and morals of the youth under their charge will exceed every other care; well considering that though goodness without knowledge is weak and feeble, yet knowledge without goodness is dangerous, and that both united form the noblest character, and lay the surest foundation of usefulness to mankind.\"<ref name=Echols/>}}\n\n===Harkness gift===\n[[File:Edward S. Harkness.jpg|thumb|[[Edward Harkness|Edward S. Harkness]], benefactor]]\nOn April 9, 1930, philanthropist and oil magnate [[Edward Harkness]] wrote to Exeter Principal [[Lewis Perry]] regarding how a substantial donation that Harkness would make to the academy might be used to fund a new way of teaching and learning:{{quote|What I have in mind is a classroom where students could sit around a table with a teacher who would talk with them and instruct them by a sort of tutorial or conference method, where each student would feel encouraged to speak up. This would be a real revolution in methods.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bass |display-authors=etal |first=Jo Ann F.|title=A declaration of readers' rights: renewing our commitment to students|year=2007|publisher=A & B/Pearson|location=Boston|isbn=978-0205499793|page=67|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o2vuAAAAMAAJ}}</ref>}}\n\nThe result was \"Harkness teaching\", in which a teacher and a group of students work together, exchanging ideas and information, similar to the [[Socratic method]]. Today at Phillips Exeter Academy, all classes are taught using this method, with no more than 12 or 13. In November 1930, Harkness gave Exeter $5.8 million to support this initiative. Since then, the academy's principal mode of instruction has been by discussion, \"seminar style,\" around an oval table known as the [[Harkness table]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/phillips-exeter-harkness-table-2014-11|title=Why the Classes at Phillips Exeter Are Different Than at Any Other Private School|work=Business Insider|access-date=April 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=The trustees of Phillips Exeter Academy |title=Phillips Exeter Academy {{!}}Harkness |url=http://www.exeter.edu/admissions/109_1220.aspx |accessdate=January 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121220030626/http://www.exeter.edu/admissions/109_1220.aspx |archivedate=December 20, 2012 }}</ref>\n[[File:Exeter Baseball.JPG|left|thumb|Exeter baseball team in 1881, including a student from the [[Chinese Educational Mission]]]] This informality was for many decades reflected in the school's \"unwritten code that there were no rules at the academy until you broke one.\"<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1986-01-05-vw-24821-story.html| last1=Lamb| first1=David| title=Exeter Remembered: Prep School Gambler Who Finally Makes His Point| newspaper=Los Angeles Times| date=January 5, 1986| access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref> Expelled alumni include the journalist [[David Lamb (journalist)|David Lamb]] and the writer and editor [[George Plimpton]].\n\n=== Recent history ===\nExeter participated in the [[Chinese Educational Mission]], hosting seven students from [[Qing dynasty|Qing China]], starting in 1879. They were sent to learn about western technology, and attended Exeter among other schools to prepare for college. However, all students were recalled after just 2 years (in 1881) due to mounting tensions between the United States and China, as well as growing concern that the students were becoming Americanized.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YMeACQAAQBAJ&pg=PT81|title=Hidden History of Exeter|last=Rimkunas|first=Barbara|date=2014|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=978-1-62585-264-9|page=81}}</ref>\n\nThe academy became coeducational in 1970 when 39 girls began attending.<ref name=\"Crimson-Coed\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.exeter.edu/libraries/4513_4622.aspx |title=Phillips Exeter Academy \u2013 Academy Chronology |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080617040752/http://www.exeter.edu/libraries/4513_4622.aspx |archivedate=June 17, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Today{{when|date=March 2019}} the student body is roughly half boys and half girls. In 1996, to reflect the academy's coeducational status, a new gender-inclusive [[Latin]] inscription ''Hic Quaerite Pueri Puellaeque Virtutem et Scientiam'' (\"Here, boys and girls, seek goodness and knowledge\") was added over the main entrance to the Academy Building.  This new inscription augments the original one \u2013 ''Huc Venite, Pueri, ut Viri Sitis'' (\"Come hither boys so that ye may become men\").<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FhmfAAAAMAAJ|title=After the Harkness Gift: A History of Phillips Exeter Academy Since 1930|last=Heskel|first=Julia|author2=Dyer, Davis|publisher=Phillips Exeter Academy|year=2008|isbn=978-0-9769787-1-8|location=Exeter, N.H.}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nExeter uses an 11-point grading system, in which an A is worth 11 points and an E is worth 0 points. Exeter has a student-to-teacher ratio of about 5:1.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/2010/04/29/best-prep-schools-2010-opinions-phillips-exeter.html|title=No. 6: Phillips Exeter Academy|last=Laneri|first=Raquel|work=Forbes|access-date=April 10, 2018|language=en}}</ref> A majority of the faculty have advanced degrees in their fields.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exeter.edu/academics/84.aspx |title=Phillips Exeter Academy \u2013 Academics |accessdate=May 6, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430224848/http://www.exeter.edu/academics/84.aspx |archivedate=April 30, 2008 }}</ref> Students who attend Exeter for four years are required to take courses in the arts, classical or modern languages, computer science, English, health & human development, history, mathematics, religion, and science. Most students receive an English diploma, but students who take the full series of Latin and Ancient Greek classes receive a Classical diploma.<ref>{{cite web|last=The trustees of Phillips Exeter Academy|title=Courses of Instruction|url=http://www.exeter.edu/academics/8919_8933.aspx|accessdate=January 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Harkness teaching method===\nMost classes at Exeter are taught around [[Harkness table]]s. No classrooms have rows of chairs, and lectures are rare. The completion of the Phelps Science Center in 2001 enabled all science classes, which previously had been taught in more conventional classrooms, to be conducted around the same Harkness tables.<ref>{{cite book|last=Crosbie|first=Michael J.|title=Architecture for science|year=2004|publisher=Images Publ|location=Mulgrave, Vic.|isbn=978-1-920744-64-9|page=192|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Ppa-moZjIAC&pg=PA193}}</ref> Elements of the Harkness method, including the Harkness table, are now used in schools around the world.<ref>{{cite web|last=St. Paul's School|title=St. Paul's School ~ Our Academic Program|url=http://www.sps.edu/podium/default.aspx?t=6187|accessdate=January 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| last=Harkness Institute| url=http://www.harknessinstitute.org/Learning_process.html|title=We learn by doing!|website=Harknessinstitute.org|accessdate=January 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Notable faculty===\n{{Main|List of Phillips Exeter Academy people#Notable faculty members and trustees of Phillips Exeter Academy}}\n\n* Founder of the Religion department [[Frederick Buechner]], minister and author<ref>''Now and Then''. Repr. San Francisco: Harper SanFrancisco, 1991. p. 47</ref>\n* Instructor in History [[Michael Golay]], historian and author<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.simonandschuster.com/authors/Michael-Golay/73457659|title=Michael Golay|website=Simon & Schuster|language=en|access-date=April 10, 2018}}</ref>\n* Instructor in English [[Todd Hearon]], poet<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poets/todd-hearon|title=Todd Hearon|date=April 9, 2018|website=Poetry Foundation|language=en-us|others=Poetry Foundation|access-date=April 10, 2018}}</ref>\n* Instructor in English [[Willie Perdomo]], poet and children's book author<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fosters.com/news/20180227/berwick-academy-to-host-poet-author-willie-perdomo|title=Berwick Academy to host poet, author Willie Perdomo|work=fosters.com|access-date=April 10, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n* Instructor in Mathematics [[Zuming Feng]], U.S. [[International Mathematical Olympiad]] Program team coach from 1997 to 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metroplexmathcircle.wordpress.com/2009/02/02/february-7-2009-dr-zuming-feng/ |title=Brief Biography of Zuming Feng from the University of Texas at Dallas |publisher=Metroplexmathcircle.wordpress.com |accessdate=August 27, 2012|date=February 3, 2009 }}</ref>\n* Instructor in Mathematics [[Gwynneth Coogan]], former Olympic athlete<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.exeter.edu/people/gwynneth-coogan-%E2%80%9983|title=Gwynneth Coogan '83|website=Phillips Exeter Academy|language=en|access-date=April 10, 2018}}</ref>\n* Instructor in Music [[Marilinda Garcia]], member of the [[New Hampshire House of Representatives]] and [[harp]] player<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unionleader.com/article/20130817/NEWHAMPSHIRE1411/130819402/0/NEWS04 |title=Salem's Rep. Garcia named Republican rising star &#124; New Hampshire Salem Observer |publisher=Unionleader.com |date=August 17, 2013 |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref>\n*Instructor in Physical Education [[Olutoyin Augustus]], former Olympic athlete<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2012/08/former_olympian_toyin_augustus.html|title=Former Olympian Toyin Augustus has raced through life nicely since Beijing|work=AL.com|access-date=April 10, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Off-campus study===\nDuring the tenure of Exeter's tenth principal, [[Richard W. Day (educator)|Richard W. Day]], the Washington Intern Program and the Foreign Studies Program began.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://pdf.phillipian.net/1973/05311973.pdf|title=Exeter Principal R.W. Day Resigns For New Career|last=|first=|date=May 31, 1973|work=[[The Phillipian]]|access-date=}}</ref> Exeter offers the Washington Intern Program, where students intern in the office of a senator or congressional representative.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://exeter.edu/news/capitol-experience|title=A Capitol Experience|work=Phillips Exeter Academy|access-date=April 10, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1981/06/07/personal-glimpses-of-washington/f7822b61-5ce3-4360-9fa5-46e462190117/|title=PERSONAL GLIMPSES OF WASHINGTON|last=Selden|first=Nathan R. W. Selden; Nathan|date=June 7, 1981|work=Washington Post|access-date=April 10, 2018|last2=16|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|last3=Academy|first3=a senior at Phillips Exeter|last4=office|first4=this year participated in its Washington intern program in the}}</ref> Exeter also participates in the [[Milton Academy]] [[The Mountain School|Mountain School]] program,<ref name=Courses-1718 /> which allows students to study in a small rural setting in [[Vershire, Vermont]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mountainschool.org/school-history/|title=School History|website=The Mountain School|language=en-US|access-date=November 28, 2017}}</ref> The academy currently sponsors trimester-long foreign study programs in [[Grenoble]], [[Tema]], [[Tokyo]], [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Stratford-upon-Avon]], [[Eleuthera]], [[Taichung]], [[G\u00f6ttingen]], [[Rome]], [[Cuenca, Ecuador|Cuenca]], and [[Callan, County Kilkenny|Callan]];<ref name=Courses-1718>{{Cite web|url=https://www.exeter.edu/sites/default/files/documents/PEA-COI-17-18-Sept-2.pdf|title=2017\u20132018 Courses of Instruction|last=Phillips Exeter Academy|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> as well as school-year abroad programs in Beijing, [[Rennes]], [[Viterbo]], and [[Zaragoza]].<ref>{{cite web|title=School Year Abroad \u2013 History |url=http://www.sya.org/s/833/index.aspx?sid=833&gid=1&pgid=730 |accessdate=January 13, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121214171807/http://www.sya.org/s/833/index.aspx?sid=833&gid=1&pgid=730 |archivedate=December 14, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sya.org/schools|title=Schools - School Year Abroad|website=www.sya.org|language=en-US|access-date=April 10, 2018}}</ref> The academy also offers foreign language summer programs in France, Japan, Spain, and Taiwan.\n\n===Numbers===\nFor the 313 members of the class of 2018, the average SAT was 730 verbal, 740 math.\n\nBetween 2016 and 2018, 15 or more students matriculated at the following colleges and universities: Brown, Carnegie Mellon, Columbia, Dartmouth, Georgetown, Harvard, MIT, Princeton, Trinity College, Tufts, Michigan, UPenn, Williams, and Yale.<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.exeter.edu/sites/default/files/documents/2018-19_Profile_for_Colleges.pdf| title=2018-19 Profile for Colleges| publisher=Phillips Exeter Academy| access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Student body==\n[[File:Philips Exeter Academy advertisement 1909.png|thumb|1909 advertisement for the school]]\n\nFor the 2016\u201317 school year, the Exeter student body included students from 45 states, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, Guam, and 34 countries. [[Person of color|Students of color]] comprise 41% of the student body<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.exeter.edu/admissions-and-financial-aid/who-we-are|title=Who We Are {{!}} Phillips Exeter Academy|website=Exeter.edu|access-date=July 1, 2017}}</ref> (Asian 23%, Black 9%, Hispanic/Latino 8%, Native American 1%).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.exeter.edu/sites/default/files/documents/facts.pdf|title=Phillips Exeter Academy Facts 2016\u20132017|last=|first=|date=|website=Exeter.edu|access-date=November 12, 2017}}</ref> [[Legacy preferences|Legacy students]] account for 13% of the students. Of new students entering in 2017 (a total of 353), 53% attended public school and 47% attended private, parochial, military, home, or foreign schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.exeter.edu/sites/default/files/documents/Facts_2017.pdf|title=Phillips Exeter Academy Facts 2017\u20132018|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMost Exeter students\u201480 percent\u2014live on campus in dormitories or houses. The remaining 19 percent of the student body are day students from the surrounding communities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.exeter.edu/documents/facts.2012_final_web(1).pdf |title=FACTS 2012~2013 |last=The trustees of Phillips Exeter Academy |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116052638/http://www.exeter.edu/documents/facts.2012_final_web%281%29.pdf |archivedate=January 16, 2013 |url-status=dead |accessdate=January 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe academy uses a unique designation for its grade levels. Entering first-year students are called Juniors (nicknamed \"preps\"), second-year students are Lower Middlers (\"lowers\"), third-year students are Upper Middlers (\"uppers\"), and fourth-year students are seniors. Exeter also admits postgraduate students (\"PGs\").<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.exeter.edu/documents/Lexicon_of_Exeter_Terminology_and_Slang_(2).pdf |title=Lexicon of Exeter Terminology and Slang |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030214937/http://exeter.edu/documents/Lexicon_of_Exeter_Terminology_and_Slang_%282%29.pdf |archivedate=October 30, 2012 |url-status=dead |accessdate=January 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Finances==\n===Tuition and financial aid===\n[[Tuition]] for boarding students in 2018-19 was $55,000, plus other mandatory and optional fees.<ref name=\"tuition2017\">{{cite web |url=https://www.exeter.edu/admissions-and-financial-aid/tuition-financial-aid |title=Phillips Exeter Academy {{!}} Tuition and Fees |accessdate=December 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228130648/https://www.exeter.edu/admissions-and-financial-aid/tuition-financial-aid |archive-date=December 28, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.boardingschoolreview.com/phillips-exeter-academy-profile| title=Phillips Exeter Academy| publisher=Boarding School Review| access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nExeter offers need-based [[Student financial aid (United States)|financial aid]]. For families with incomes less than $75,000, Exeter is free.<ref>{{cite web |last=The trustees of Phillips Exeter Academy |title=Phillips Exeter Academy {{!}} Tuition and Financial Aid |url=http://www.exeter.edu/admissions/109_7844.aspx |accessdate=January 6, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DTMMmxgp?url=http://www.exeter.edu/admissions/109_7844.aspx |archivedate=January 6, 2013}}</ref> Partial assistance is available for families with incomes up to $200,000. Admissions are currently [[Need-blind admission|need-blind]].<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.boardingschoolreview.com/blog/understanding-financial-aid| last1=Kennedy| first1=Robert| title=Understanding Financial Aid| date=February 21, 2019| access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref> In 2018, approximately 50 percent of students received a total of $21 million in financial assistance.<ref name=\"tuition2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.exeter.edu/admissions-and-financial-aid/tuition-financial-aid|title=Phillips Exeter Academy {{!}} Tuition and Fees|accessdate=October 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Endowment===\nExeter's [[financial endowment|endowment]] as of June 30, 2017, was valued at $1.3 billion.<ref name=Facts/> This is the third-highest endowment of any American secondary school, behind the $11.0 billion endowment of [[Kamehameha Schools]] in Hawaii,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ksbe.edu/allpdfs/annualreport04/6_strengthening_endowment.pdf |title=KS AR 2004-PDF prep 01.indd |accessdate=August 27, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326063436/http://www.ksbe.edu/allpdfs/annualreport04/6_strengthening_endowment.pdf |archivedate=March 26, 2009 }}</ref> and the $7.8 billion of the [[Milton Hershey School]] in [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=Fabrikant>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/26/business/26prep.html?ex=1359090000&en=a3048da438b5a526&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink | title=At Elite Prep Schools, College-Size Endowments | last=Fabrikant | first=Geraldine | date=January 26, 2008 |periodical=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=January 29, 2008 | ref=harv }}</ref> Phillips Exeter Academy's operational budget was $107 million as of 2018.<ref name=Facts/>\n\n==Campus facilities==\n[[File:Exeter Tree Halo.jpg|thumb|upright|The Academy Building]]\n[[File:Exeter library interior.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Phillips Exeter Academy Library|The Class of 1945 Library]]]]\n\n===Academic facilities===\n* The '''Academy Building''' is the fourth such building. It was built in 1914 after a devastating fire ruined the third. The Academy Building was designed by [[Ralph Adams Cram]] of Cram, Goodhue & Ferguson,<ref name=Aten>{{cite book| last=Aten| first=Carol Walker| title=Postcards from Exeter| year=2003| publisher=Arcadia| location=Portsmouth, NH| isbn=978-0-7385-3481-7| page=45| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_nE2qbeXR9YC&pg=PA44}}</ref> and houses the History, Math, Religion and Classical Languages departments, along with a small but significant [[archaeology]]/[[anthropology]] museum.<ref>{{cite web| title=Rooms with a View \u2013 A Portfolio of Exeter Classrooms| url=http://www.exeter.edu/documents/Exeter_Bulletin/Classroom_Portraits_Fall_07.pdf| accessdate=January 7, 2013| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309090316/http://exeter.edu/documents/Exeter_Bulletin/Classroom_Portraits_Fall_07.pdf| archivedate=March 9, 2013| df=mdy-all}}</ref> Two wings were added to the original structure in the 1920s and 1930s during a building boom that was orchestrated by Principal Lewis Perry. One of these wings is the Mayer Art Center, which, despite being attached to the Academy Building, is often referred to as a separate building. The Academy Building also houses the Assembly Hall (formerly known as the Chapel). In former times, non-denominational, Christian religious services were conducted in the Chapel every morning Monday through Saturday before the beginning of classes, and attendance was mandatory for all students in keeping with the wishes of the founders of the academy. The bell (visible in the photo of the Academy Building tower) was rung in a succession of rings to call the student body to worship: Ones, Twos, Threes, Fours, and Fives. After Fives were rung, monitors would begin walking down the rows checking attendance on the benches. The bell continues to be rung to mark the end of classes, as well as to mark each hour from 8 AM to 11 PM.\n* The '''[[Phillips Exeter Academy Library|Class of 1945 Library]]''', a famous modern library designed by [[Louis Kahn]]. The library has a shelf capacity of 250,000 volumes, and as of 2009 housed 162,000 volumes. This library is the largest secondary-school library in the world. When it opened, Ada Louise Huxtable, architecture critic for ''The New York Times'', hailed the Exeter library as a \"serene, distinguished structure of considerable beauty.\" She said that the library's central space \"breaks on the viewer with breathtaking drama.\" The headline of her review called the Exeter library a \"stunning paean to books.\"<ref>{{cite book| last=Huxtable| first=Ada Louise| title=On architecture: collected reflections on a century of change| year=2008| publisher=Walker| location=New York| isbn=978-0-8027-1707-8| page=188| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t2nDO99m5-cC&pg=PA188| edition=1st U.S.}}</ref>\n*'''Elizabeth Phillips Academy Center''' (or \"EPAC\") is the student center of the campus. It houses the Phelps Commons, the McLane Post Office, the Day Student Lounge, the Forum (a 300-person auditorium), the Academic Support Center, and a grill. It also plays host to a number of student organizations such as [[The Exonian]], [[WPEA]], and the Exeter Student Service Organization (ESSO). The building was originally opened in 2006 as the Phelps Academy Center, but the name was changed in the fall of 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.exeter.edu/campus/facilities/community-spaces|title=Community Hubs|website=Phillips Exeter Academy|language=en|access-date=September 8, 2018}}</ref>\n*'''Goel Center for Theater and Dance''' was opened in 2018. It houses DRAMAT, the student led drama club at Exeter. It is named for [[David Goel]] and Stacey Goel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.exeter.edu/about-us/our-campus/south-campus-renewal/south-campus-facilities/center-theater-and-dance|title=Goel Center for Theater and Dance|website=Phillips Exeter Academy|language=en|access-date=September 8, 2018}}</ref>\n* '''Phillips Hall''' is home to the English and Modern Languages departments. On the first floor of Phillips Hall is the Elting Room (where the faculty meets). Phillips Hall was built in 1932 during the tenure of Principal Lewis Perry. The Harkness gift funded the building, and its classrooms were designed for the Harkness tables.\n* '''Phelps Science Center''' was designed by [[Centerbrook Architects & Planners]], and was built in 2001. The center provides laboratory and classroom space. In 2004, it received the [[American Institute of Architects]] New Hampshire's Honor Award for Excellence in Architecture.<ref>{{cite web| last=Centerbrook Architects and Planners| title=Centerbrook Architects and Planners > Complete List of Awards| url=http://www.centerbrook.com/about/awards_list| accessdate=January 2, 2013}}</ref>\n* '''Forrestal Bowld Music Center''' houses the Music Department, the Music Library, three rehearsal halls, several faculty offices, and dozens of rehearsal rooms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exeter.edu/map/link/forrestalbowldlink.html|title=Tour|website=Exeter.edu|accessdate=January 7, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130601121050/http://www.exeter.edu/map/link/forrestalbowldlink.html|archivedate=June 1, 2013}}</ref> It was built in 1995, and was awarded the Honor Award in Architecture Design by the [[Boston Society of Architects]] in 1996. The facility was extended recently and includes a recital hall.\n* '''Mayer Art Center''' is home to the Art Department and the [[Lamont Gallery]], as well as the College Counseling Office. It was constructed in 1903 as Alumni Hall. It contains a large ceramics studio with approximately twenty wheels and three kilns on the first floor, two printmaking studios and three drawing/painting studios on the second floor, and an architectural and 3-D design studio on the third floor. It also has a 3-D printer, which was added in 2013.\n\n===Athletic facilities===\n* The '''George H. Love Gymnasium''' was built in 1969, and is named for [[George H. Love]] (1917).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/07/27/obituaries/george-h-love-90-industrialist-who-headed-two-corporations.html|title=George H. Love, 90, Industrialist Who Headed Two Corporations|last=Fowler|first=Glenn|date=July 27, 1991|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 12, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> It houses [[Squash (sport)|squash]] facilities with 10 international sized courts, one [[swimming pool]], three [[basketball]] courts, a weight-training room, a sports-science lab, gym offices, two [[ice hockey|hockey]] rinks, locker rooms, and visiting team locker rooms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kmwarch.com/project.aspx?cat=2&id=3|title=Phillips Exeter Academy George H. Love'18 Athletic Facility, Exeter by Kallmann McKinnell & Wood Architects|website=www.kmwarch.com|access-date=February 12, 2018}}</ref>\n* The '''Thompson Gymnasium''' was built in 1918, replacing the old gym which was demolished in 1922, and was a gift of Colonel [[William Boyce Thompson]] (1890). It has a basketball court, a dance studio, visiting team locker rooms, a cycling training room, a second swimming pool and a media room.<ref name=Aten />\n* The '''Thompson Cage''' was built in 1931 and was also a gift of Colonel Thompson. It is an indoor cage with two tracks; one has a wooden surface and the other a dirt surface. The open dirt-surfaced floor is a multipurpose area. A [[wrestling]] room and gymnastics space are attached. In 2015, Academy Trustees approved the removal of the Cage and the construction of a new field house in its footprint.\n* '''The''' '''Thompson Fieldhouse''' was opened in 2018 on the grounds of the former Thompson Cage. It is an 84,574 square-foot facility connected to the Love and Thompson Gymnasiums, housing four indoor tennis courts, two batting cages, a wrestling room, and an indoor track.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://exeter.edu/news/new-field-house-opens-exeter|title=New field house opens at Exeter {{!}} Phillips Exeter Academy|website=exeter.edu|language=en|access-date=February 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.exeter.edu/about-us/our-campus/south-campus-renewal/south-campus-facilities/athletic-field-house|title=Athletic Field House {{!}} Phillips Exeter Academy|website=www.exeter.edu|language=en|access-date=February 12, 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228194335/https://www.exeter.edu/about-us/our-campus/south-campus-renewal/south-campus-facilities/athletic-field-house|archivedate=December 28, 2017}}</ref>\n* '''Ralph Lovshin Track''' is an outdoor all-weather 400-m track named for the long-serving track coach Ralph Lovshin.\n* The '''Plimpton Playing Fields''' are used for various outdoor sports. They are named in honor of alumnus and trustee [[George Arthur Plimpton]] (1873).<ref name=Aten />\n* '''Phelps Stadium''' is used for [[American football|football]], [[soccer]], [[lacrosse]] and [[field hockey]]. It was converted into turf surface in 2006.\n* The '''William G. Saltonstall Boathouse''' was built in 1990, and is the center of [[rowing (sport)|crew]] on campus, on the [[Squamscott River]]. It is named for the academy's [[William Saltonstall|ninth principal]].<ref name=Aten />\n* '''Amos Alonzo Stagg Baseball Diamond''' was named after alumnus [[Amos Alonzo Stagg]].\n* '''Hilliard Lacrosse Field'''\n* '''Roger Nekton Championship Pool''' is named for the long-serving former swimming and [[water polo]] coach.\n* The '''Downer Family Fitness Center''' was built in 2015 guided by a donation from its namesake, the Downer family. It features many weight lifting resources, aerobic machines, and turf space.\n* 19 outdoor tennis courts\n* Several miles of cross-country and running trails\n* Wrestling practice room<ref>{{cite web|last=The trustees of Phillips Exeter Academy |title=Phillips Exeter Academy {{!}} Athletic Facilities |url=http://www.exeter.edu/athletics/185_4201.aspx |accessdate=January 6, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DTMDa3Zw?url=http://www.exeter.edu/athletics/185_4201.aspx |archivedate=January 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Other facilities===\n[[File:Phillips Church, Exeter, NH.jpg|thumb|Phillips Church in 1911]]\n[[File:View from Tower of Phillips Church, Exeter, NH.jpg|thumb|View from the tower of Phillips Church in 1911, showing Alumni Hall (1903, now Mayer Art Center), and third Academy Building (1872\u20131914)]]\n[[File:Abbot hall.jpg|thumb|Abbot Hall]]\n\n* '''Phillips Church''' was originally built as the Second Parish Church in 1897 and was purchased by the academy in 1922.<ref name=Aten /> The building was designed by [[Ralph Adams Cram]]. Although originally a church, the building now contains spaces for students of many faiths.  It includes a [[Hinduism|Hindu]] shrine, a [[Islam|Muslim]] prayer room and ablutions fountain, a [[kashrut|kosher]] kitchen, and a meditation room.  Services that are particular to Phillips Church include Evening Prayer on Tuesday nights, Thursday Meditation, and Indaba\u2014a religious open forum.\n* '''Nathaniel Gilman House''' was built in 1740. The [[Gilman House]] is a large colonial white clapboard home with a [[gambrel]] roof hipped at one end, a leaded [[fanlight]] over the front door and a wide panelled entry hall.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NVNm_97RrcwC&pg=PA163 |title=New Hampshire: A Guide to the Granite State, Federal Writers' Project, Houghton Mifflin Company, Boston, 1938|isbn=9781603540285|year=1938}}</ref> This home, as well as the Benjamin Clark Gilman House which is also owned by the academy, were built for members of Exeter's Gilman family, who donated the Nathaniel Gilman House to the academy in 1905. The home now houses the academy's Alumni and Alumnae Affairs and Development Office.\n* The '''Davis Center''' was designed by [[Ralph Adams Cram]] as the Davis Library. Today it houses the financial aid offices as well as the dance studio.\n\n==Athletics==\nExeter offers 65 interscholastic sports teams at the varsity and junior varsity level, 27 intramural sports teams, and various fitness classes. All students are required to participate in athletics.\n\nWater polo, wrestling, swimming, cycling, soccer, squash, cross country, [[rowing (sport)|crew]], and ice hockey teams have won recent New England championships.<ref>{{cite web|title=Race Results Report |url=http://results.usrowing.org/RaceResults/2008YouthResults.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508210259/http://results.usrowing.org/RaceResults/2008YouthResults.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 8, 2012 |accessdate=January 7, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nExeter has graduated multiple elite athletes in the past few decades. For example, crew Olympians include [[Anne Marden]] '76, [[Rajanya Shah]] '92, [[Sabrina Kolker]] '98, and [[Andr\u00e9anne Morin]] '02. [[Georgia Gould]] is an Olympic medalist in mountain biking, while [[Joy Fahrenkrog]] is a member of the United States Archery Team. [[Duncan Robinson (basketball)|Duncan Robinson]] plays for the [[Miami Heat]] in the [[National Basketball Association]]. [[Tom Cavanagh (ice hockey)|Tom Cavanagh]] played in the [[National Hockey League]]. [[Sam Fuld]] played 8 years of [[Major League Baseball]].\n\n[[Image:ExeterAndover1903.jpg|thumb|upright|1903 football poster]]\nExeter's main rival is [[Phillips Academy]] (Andover). The two schools have been competing against each other in both baseball and football since 1878 (in those first games, Exeter defeated Andover 12\u20130 in baseball, while Andover won the football game, 22-0).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exeter.edu/libraries/553_4389.aspx |title=Academy Chronology |publisher=Phillips Exeter Academy |accessdate=November 22, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DTM3nZi4?url=http://www.exeter.edu/libraries/553_4389.aspx |archivedate=January 6, 2013 }}</ref> Today, Andover-Exeter weekend is still a large tradition in both schools.\n\nOther athletic opponents include a variety of New England private schools such as [[Belmont Hill School]], [[Berwick Academy (Maine)|Berwick Academy]], [[Deerfield Academy]], [[Northfield Mount Hermon]], [[Brewster Academy]], [[Choate Rosemary Hall]], [[Groton School]], [[The Governor's Academy]], [[Loomis Chaffee]], [[Tabor Academy, Massachusetts|Tabor Academy]], [[Milton Academy]], [[Avon Old Farms]], [[Worcester Academy]], [[Cushing Academy]], and various other [[northeastern United States|northeastern]] prep and boarding schools.<ref>{{cite web|title=Phillips Exeter Academy {{!}} Go Big Red!|url=http://www.exeter.edu/athletics/185.aspx|accessdate=January 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\nExeter had a gendered [[dress code]] until June 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title= Gender-Neutral Dress Code a First for PEA|last=The Exonian May 14, 2015|url=http://theexonian.com/2015/05/14/gender-neutral-dress-code-a-first-for-pea/|date=May 14, 2015}}</ref> Boys were required to wear collared shirts and ties or turtlenecks. Girls were required to wear non-revealing, appropriate attire. Skirts and shorts must reach finger-tip length, and straps may not be less than two fingers wide.  Jeans were allowed for boys and girls; however, \"hoodies,\" graphic T-shirts, and athletic wear are not permitted. The new dress code is gender neutral, and no longer requires ties. Dress code is required only in the classroom setting and Assembly.<ref name=\"exeter\">{{cite web|last=Phillips Exeter Academy|title=The E Book 2012\u20132013|url=http://www.exeter.edu/documents/EBook.pdf|accessdate=January 2, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121224005633/http://www.exeter.edu/documents/EBook.pdf|archivedate=December 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe academy has over 100 clubs listed. The number of functioning and reputable clubs fluctuates; several of the listed clubs on the website do not hold tables on Club Night. ''[[The Exonian]]'' is the school's weekly newspaper. It is the oldest continuously-running preparatory school newspaper in the United States, having begun publishing in 1878. Recently, ''The Exonian'' began online publication.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theexonian.com/|title=The Exonian|work=theexonian.com}}</ref> Other long-established clubs include ESSO, which focuses on social service outreach; and the PEAN, which is the academy's yearbook. Exeter also has the oldest surviving secondary school society, the Golden Branch (founded in 1818), a society for public speaking, inspired by PEA's Rhetorical Society of 1807\u20131820. Now known as the [[Daniel Webster Debate Society]], these groups served as America's first secondary school organization for [[Public speaking|oratory]] and prepared students for the communication skills required for success at [[Harvard University]].<ref>{{harv|Echols|1970|p=21}}</ref> The [[Model UN]] club has won the \"Best Small Delegation\" award at [[Harvard International Relations Council#Harvard Model United Nations|HMUN]].<ref name=\"exonian\">{{cite web|last=Phillips Exeter Academy|title=The Exonian|url=https://theexonian.com/2017/02/02/exeter-sweeps-at-hmun/|accessdate=April 2, 2017|date=February 2, 2017}}</ref> Exeter's Mock Trial Association, founded by attorney and historian Walter Stahr,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peamt.org/about-us/|title=About Us|website=PEA Mock Trial|language=en-US|access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> has since 2011 claimed seventeen individual titles, five all-around state titles, and a top-ten spot at the National High School Mock Trial Championship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.theexonian.com/cgi-bin/exeter?a=d&d=txn20130609-01.2.227&srpos=10&e=-------en-20--1--txt-txIN-Mock++Trial------|title=The Exonian 9 June 2013 \u2014 The Exonian Archives|website=archive.theexonian.com|access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nClose to 80% of students live in the dormitories, with the other 20% commuting from homes within a {{convert|30|mi|km|adj=on|-1}} radius. Each residence hall has several faculty members and senior student proctors. There are check-in hours of 8:00 pm (for first- and second-year students), 9:00pm (for third years), and 10:00 pm (for seniors) during the weekdays and 11:00 pm on Saturday night.<ref name=\"exeter\" />\n\n[[File:Phillips Exeter Academy Panorama.jpg|thumb|center|750px|Student body, Phillips Exeter Academy, ca. 1903]]\n\nReligious life on campus is supported by the Religious Services Department, which provides a vintage stone chapel and a full-service ministry for the spiritual needs of students.<ref name=\"Phillips Church\">\"[https://www.exeter.edu/student-life/campus-connections/phillips-church Phillips Church],\" ''Phillips Exeter Academy,'' 2017. Retrieved June 22, 2017.</ref> The chapel was originally built in 1895 and has been updated. It accommodates worship for \"twelve religious traditions including Christian, Muslim, Jewish, Hindu, Quaker, Buddhist, Catholic among others\"<ref>\"[https://www.cramandferguson.com/philips-church/ Phillips Church at Phillips Exeter Academy: Exeter, NH],\" ''Cram and Ferguson Architects.'' Retrieved June 22, 2017.</ref> as well as Secular Humanism.<ref name=\"Phillips Church\"/>\n\nWeekly attendance at the religious service of their choice was required of students until 1969, after which religion at Exeter languished until it was revived by a new approach \"as concerned with the religious dimension of all of our lives as it is with the particular religious needs of any one of us.\" A renovation of Phillips Church, completed in 2002, provided spaces for worship and meditation for students of diverse religious persuasions.<ref>Oppenheimer, Mark. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/12/us/at-phillips-exeter-a-world-of-religious-diversity.html At Phillips Exeter, a World of Religious Diversity],\" ''The New York Times,'' April 11, 2014. Retrieved June 22, 2017.</ref>\n\n==Sexual misconduct==\nExeter has struggled to effectively deal with multiple incidents in which students were sexually abused by faculty and staff.\n\nAn incident of sexual misconduct that occurred in the basement of the church in late 2015 first brought criticism to the school.<ref>{{Cite news| last1=Abelson| first1=Jenn| url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2016/07/12/phillips-exeter-academy-under-fire-again-for-its-handling-sexual-misconduct-allegations/UlfO1FgtbFEvWAQcEK7grN/story.html| title=Phillips Exeter Academy under fire again for its handling of sexual misconduct allegations| newspaper=The Boston Globe| date=July 13, 2016| access-date=June 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nA more in-depth investigation by an outside law firm uncovered sexual misconduct that occurred at Exeter since the 1970s and involved at least 11 members of the faculty and staff. The report harshly criticized the school for not supporting the victims when they reported the incidents and for a pattern of not including these allegations in the faculty members' files. Apparently, the school maintained two sets of files, and would keep the more sensitive material away from Human Resources and prospective employers. Typically, faculty members would then leave Exeter but get hired at peer schools. In at least one case, the teacher then molested students at his next school. The school has apologized.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/phillips-exeter-academy-new-hampshire-former-staffers-accused-of-abuse-2018-08-25/| title=11 former New Hampshire prep school staffers accused of abuse| work=CBS News| date=August 25, 2018| access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/14/us/phillips-exeter-sex-assault.html| last1=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a| first1=Richard| title=Phillips Exeter Deans Failed to Report Sex Assault Case, Police Say| date=November 14, 2017| access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Emblems==\n\n===Academy seal===\nExeter has two chief symbols: a seal depicting a river, sun and [[beehive]], incorporating the academy's mottos; and the ''Lion Rampant''. The seal has similarities to that used by Phillips Academy\u2014an emblem designed by [[Paul Revere]]\u2014and its imagery is [[Masonic]] in nature. A beehive often represented the industry and cooperation of a lodge or, in this case, the studies and united efforts of Academy students. The ''Lion Rampant'' is derived from the Phillips family's [[coat of arms]], and suggests that all of the academy's alumni are part of the \"Exonian family\".\n\nExeter has three mottoes on the academy seal: ''Non Sibi'' (Latin 'Not for oneself') indicating a life based on community and duty; ''Finis origine pendet'' (Latin 'The end depends on the beginning') reflecting Exeter's emphasis on hard work as preparation for a fruitful adult life; and ''\u03a7\u03ac\u03c1\u03b9\u03c4\u03b9 \u0398\u03b5\u03bf\u1fe6'' (Greek 'By the grace of God') reflecting Exeter's Calvinist origins, of which the only remnant today is the school's requirement that most students take two courses in religion or philosophy.<ref>{{cite web|last=The Trustees of Phillips Exeter Academy|title=Phillips Exeter Academy {{!}} Academy Archives|url=https://www.exeter.edu/academics/library/archives-special-collections|accessdate=January 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===School colors and the alumnus tie===\nThere are several variants of school colors associated with Phillips Exeter Academy that range from crimson red and white to burgundy red and silver. Black is also a color associated with the school to a lesser extent. The official school colors are lively maroon and gray. The traditional school tie is a burgundy red tie with alternating diagonal silver stripes and silver lions rampant.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n[[File:Abraham Lincoln letter Exeter New Hampshire.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Letter from President [[Abraham Lincoln]] to [[Mary Todd Lincoln]], written from [[Exeter, New Hampshire|Exeter]], where Lincoln was visiting son [[Robert Todd Lincoln]], then an Exeter student. March 1860]]\n{{Main|List of Phillips Exeter Academy people#Notable alumni}}\n\nEarly alumni of Exeter include US Senator [[Daniel Webster]] (1796);<ref>{{cite dictionary|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=W000238|title=WEBSTER, Daniel, (1782\u20131852)|dictionary=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=December 14, 2013}}</ref> [[John Adams Dix]] (1809)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/memoirsjohnadam02dixgoog|title=Memoirs of John Adams Dix|last=Dix|first=Morgan|date=1883|publisher=Harper & Brothers|language=en}}</ref> a [[United States Secretary of the Treasury|Secretary of the Treasury]] and [[Governor of New York]]; US President [[Franklin Pierce]] (1820);<ref>{{cite web|url=http://totallyhistory.com/franklin-pierce/|title=Franklin Pierce|publisher=Totally History|accessdate=December 14, 2013|date=September 28, 2011}}</ref> [[Abraham Lincoln]]'s son and 35th [[United States Secretary of War|Secretary of War]] [[Robert Lincoln]] (1860);<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.seacoastonline.com/article/20100305/NEWS/3050330|title=Whatever happened to Robert Todd Lincoln?|work=seacoastonline.com|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref> [[Ulysses S. Grant, Jr.]] (1870);<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AzPd0aVnOl0C&pg=PA73|title=All the Presidents' Children: Triumph and Tragedy in the Lives of America's First Families|last=Wead|first=Doug|date=January 6, 2004|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-0-7434-4633-4|page=73}}</ref> Richard and Francis [[Grover Cleveland|Cleveland]];<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NVNm_97RrcwC&pg=PA163|title=New Hampshire: A Guide to the Granite State, Federal Writers' Project, Houghton Mifflin Company, Boston, 1938|isbn=978-1-60354-028-5|page=163| year=1938}}</ref> \"grandfather of football\" [[Amos Alonzo Stagg]] (1880);<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1932/12/16/archives/stagg-at-exeter-dinner-football-coach-tells-academy-alumni-of-his.html|title=STAGG AT EXETER DINNER.; Football Coach Tells Academy Alumni of His Student Days.|last=|first=|date=December 16, 1932|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref> [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning author [[Booth Tarkington]] (1889)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ibj.com/articles/60109-booth-tarkington-hoosier-novelist|title=HOOSIER BEACON: Booth Tarkington, Hoosier novelist|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref> and [[Hugo W. Koehler]] (1903), American naval spy during the [[Russian Revolution]] and step-father of [[United States Senator]] [[Claiborne Pell]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Phillips Exeter Academy|title=General Catalogue of the Officers and Students of the Phillips Exeter Academy. 1783\u20131903|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ILjOAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA186|year=1903|publisher=News-letter Press|page=186}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Harvard College (1780- ). Class of 1907|title=Secretary's Fourth Report|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CcknAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA216|year=1917|publisher=Plimpton Press|page=216}}</ref> [[John Knowles]], author of ''[[A Separate Peace]]'' and ''[[Peace Breaks Out]]'', was a 1945 graduate; both novels are set at the fictional Devon School, which serves as an analog for his [[alma mater]].<ref name=\"Magrone\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.seacoastonline.com/article/20011204/News/312049973|title=Author John Knowles dies|last=Magrone|first=Callie|work=seacoastonline.com|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nExeter alumni pursue careers in various fields. Other alumni noted for their work in government include [[Gifford Pinchot]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fs.usda.gov/detail/greytowers/aboutgreytowers/history/?cid=stelprd3824502|title=Gifford Pinchot (1865\u20131946)|last=|first=|date=2018|website=United States Department of Agriculture Forest Service|access-date=}}</ref> [[Lewis Cass]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_6UZAAAAAIAAJ|title=General Catalogue of Officers and Students, 1783\u20131903|last=Phillips Exeter Academy|publisher=Phillips Exeter Academy|year=1903|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_6UZAAAAAIAAJ/page/n87 75]}}</ref> [[Judd Gregg]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1876822,00.html|title=Commerce Secretary Judd Gregg|last=Altman|first=Alex|date=February 4, 2009|work=Time|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0040-781X}}</ref> [[Jay Rockefeller]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/07/21/magazine/rockefeller-s-assets.html|title=Rockefeller's Assets|last=Toner|first=Robin|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref> [[Kent Conrad]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bismarcktribune.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/conrad-s-early-career-marked-by-win-pledge/article_d7e4ba92-4b8f-11e2-9c2b-001a4bcf887a.html|title=Conrad's early career marked by 1986 win, pledge|last=Smith|first=Nick|work=Bismarck Tribune|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref> [[John Negroponte]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/2007/01/29/for-negroponte-move-to-state-dept-is-a-homecoming/f7a692fb-a6b7-4bcf-bf60-60725e6be8d0/|title=For Negroponte, Move to State Dept. Is a Homecoming|last=Blumenfeld|first=Laura|date=January 29, 2007|work=Washington Post|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> [[Bobby Shriver]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JZmXCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA101|title=RFK Jr.: Robert F. Kennedy Jr. and the Dark Side of the Dream|last=Oppenheimer|first=Jerry|date=2015|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=978-1-250-03295-9|page=101}}</ref> [[Robert Bauer]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/bob-bauer/gIQAgz4w6O_topic.html|title=Bob Bauer|date=July 26, 2012|website=Washington Post|language=EN|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> and [[Peter Orszag]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govexec.com/story_page.cfm?articleid=41454&dcn=todaysnews|title=Obama expected to name Peter Orszag OMB director (11/18/08)|date=|publisher=GovExec.com|accessdate=January 21, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606132136/http://www.govexec.com/story_page.cfm?articleid=41454&dcn=todaysnews|archive-date=June 6, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Alumni notable for their military service include Secretary of Navy [[George Bancroft]], [[Benjamin Butler]],<ref>West, Richard Sedgewick (1965).&nbsp;''Lincoln's Scapegoat General: A Life of Benjamin F. Butler, 1818\u20131893''. Boston: Houghton Mifflin.</ref> and [[Charles C. Krulak]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usna.edu/Notables/commandants/1964krulak.php|title=Charles C. Krulak :: Notable Graduates :: USNA|website=www.usna.edu|language=en|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> Authors [[George Plimpton]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2003/10/06/george-plimpton|title=George Plimpton|last=Remnick|first=David|date=September 29, 2003|work=The New Yorker|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref> [[John Knowles]],<ref name=\"Magrone\"/> [[Gore Vidal]],<ref>''Gore Vidal: A Critical Companion'' Susan Baker, Curtis S. Gibson. Greenwood Publishing Group, 1997. {{ISBN|0-313-29579-4}}. p. 3.</ref> [[John Irving]] (whose stepfather taught at Exeter),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://unhmagazine.unh.edu/f05/johnirving.html|title=Becoming John Irving|website=unhmagazine.unh.edu|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> [[Robert Woodruff Anderson|Robert Anderson]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/10/theater/10anderson.html|title=Robert Anderson, Playwright of 'Tea and Sympathy,' Dies at 91|last=Weber|first=Bruce|date=February 10, 2009|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Dan Brown]] (whose father taught at Exeter),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/when-dan-brown-came-to-visit|title=When Dan Brown Came to Visit|last=Rothman|first=Joshua|date=June 21, 2013|work=The New Yorker|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref> [[Peter Benchley]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.harpercollins.com/cr-100425/nathaniel-benchley|title=Nathaniel Benchley|website=HarperCollins US|language=en|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> [[James Agee]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ageefilms.org/ageebio.html|title=Agee FIlms: Agee Chronology|website=www.ageefilms.org|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> [[Chang-Rae Lee]],<ref>Wu, Yung-Hsing. \"Chang-rae Lee.\" Asian- American Writers. Ed. Deborah L. Madsen. Detroit: Gale, 2005. Dictionary of Literary Biography Vol. 312. Literature Resource Center. Web. April 19, 2014.</ref> [[Debby Herbenick]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://exeter.edu/about-us/our-commitment-safety/how-we-educate-students|title=How We Educate Students|website=Phillips Exeter Academy|language=en|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> [[Stewart Brand]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sb.longnow.org/SB_homepage/Bio.html|title=Bio...|website=sb.longnow.org|language=en|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> [[Norb Vonnegut]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newmancom.com/2011/07/18/book-tour-for-best-selling-author-norb-vonnegut/|title=Book tour for best-selling author, Norb Vonnegut \u00bb Newman Communications|website=newmancom.com|language=en|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> and [[Roland Merullo]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rolandmerullo.com/index-1.html|title=About|website=rolandmerullo.com|language=en|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> also attended the academy.\n\nOther notable alumni include businessmen [[Joseph Coors]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2012/09/22/joe-coors-jr-former-black-sheep-of-family-now-running-for-office/|title=Joe Coors Jr., former black sheep of family, now running for office|date=September 22, 2012|work=The Denver Post|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> [[Michael Lynton]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http: