/documents/Exeter_Bulletin/alumni_profiles/forbes_88.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304040537/http://exeter.edu/documents/Exeter_Bulletin/alumni_profiles/forbes_88.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 4, 2016|title=The Exeter Bulletin Online|date=March 4, 2016|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> [[Ketch Secor]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/how-ketch-secor-started-wild-roots-band-old-crow-medicine-show-20140721|title=How Ketch Secor Started Wild Roots Band Old Crow Medicine Show|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> [[Win Butler]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/nymetro/news/people/columns/intelligencer/14585/index2.html|title=Intelligencer: September 26 \u2013 October 3, 2005|website=NYMag.com|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> and [[William Butler (musician)|William Butler]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.northwestern.edu/magazine/winter2012/feature/all-fired-up_print.html|title=All Fired Up: Northwestern Magazine - Northwestern University|website=www.northwestern.edu|access-date=February 20, 2018}}</ref> historians [[Robert Cowley]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1978/06/25/archives/edith-p-lorillard-wed-to-robert-cowley.html|title=Edith P. Lorillard Wed to Robert Cowley.|date=June 25, 1978|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Arthur Schlesinger, Jr.]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/01/washington/01schlesinger.html|title=Arthur Schlesinger, Historian of Power, Dies at 89|last=Martin|first=Douglas|date=March 1, 2007|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and [[Brooks D. Simpson]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://issuu.com/exeterbulletin/docs/winter12bulletin/23|title=The Exeter Bulletin, winter 2012|work=Issuu|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref> writers [[Roxane Gay]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bombmagazine.org/article/10067/roxane-gay,|title=Roxane Gay|author=John Freeman|date=Summer 2014|newspaper=Bomb|access-date=April 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304202503/http://bombmagazine.org/article/10067/roxane-gay,|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Joyce Maynard]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-02-11/features/9201130601_1_autobiographical-columns-joyce-maynard-yale-freshman|title=Joyce Maynard Bounces Back With Another Chapter|work=tribunedigital-chicagotribune|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref> screenwriters [[Tom Whedon]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jhECBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA11|title=Joss Whedon: The Biography|last=Pascale|first=Amy|date=August 1, 2014|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=978-1-61374-104-7|page=11}}</ref> and [[Tom Mankiewicz]];<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Mankiewicz}}</ref>{{Circular reference|date=December 2019}} baseball players [[Red Rolfe|Robert Rolfe]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/f388510d|title=Red Rolfe {{!}} Society for American Baseball Research|website=sabr.org|language=en|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> and [[Sam Fuld]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhmagazine.com/July-2011/Super-Sam-Sam-Fuld/|title=Super Sam - Sam Fuld - New Hampshire Magazine - July 2011|website=www.nhmagazine.com|language=en|access-date=April 7, 2018|date=July 2011}}</ref> educators [[Jared Sparks]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TZoaAQAAIAAJ|title=The Life and Writings of Jared Sparks: Comprising Selections from His Journals and Correspondence|last=Adams|first=Herbert Baxter|date=1970|publisher=Books for Libraries Press|language=en}}</ref> and [[Benno C. Schmidt, Jr.]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/12/10/us/yale-said-to-pick-benno-schmidt-as-president.html|title=YALE SAID TO PICK BENNO SCHMIDT AS PRESIDENT|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref> composer [[Adam Guettel]];<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-1002284517|title=Guettel, Adam {{!}} Grove Music|language=en|doi=10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.A2284517|access-date=April 7, 2018|year=2015|last1=Warfield|first1=Scott}}</ref> humorist [[Greg Daniels]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://exeter.edu/news/exeter-explorations-2014-bringing-new-perspectives-back-campus|title=Exeter Explorations: Bringing New Perspectives Back to Campus|work=Phillips Exeter Academy|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref> mathematicians [[Shinichi Mochizuki]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://projectwordsworth.com/the-paradox-of-the-proof/|title=The Paradox of the Proof|date=May 5, 2013|work=Project Wordsworth|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> [[David Mumford]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shawprize.org/en/shaw.php?tmp=3&twoid=51&threeid=63&fourid=107&fiveid=24|title=The Shaw Prize \u2013 Top prizes for astronomy, life science and mathematics|website=www.shawprize.org|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> and [[Lloyd Shapley]], winner of the 2012 Nobel Prize in economics;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.informs.org/Explore/History-of-O.R.-Excellence/Biographical-Profiles/Shapley-Lloyd-S.|title=Shapley, Lloyd S.|last=INFORMS|website=INFORMS|language=en-US|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> economist [[Paul Romer]], winner of the 2018 Nobel Prize in economics,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2018/10/08/nobel-prize-economics-william-nordhaus-paul-romer-mit-phillips-exeter-academy/|title=2 Researchers With MIT Ties Win Nobel Prize for Economics|date=October 8, 2018|access-date=October 8, 2018|language=en}}</ref> computer scientist [[Adam D'Angelo]] (co-founder of [[Quora]]);<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/adam-dangelo/|title=Adam D'Angelo|work=Forbes|access-date=April 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref> and philosopher and evolutionary biologist [[Daniel Dennett]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newphilosopher.com/articles/the-secret-of-consciousness-with-daniel-c-dennett/|title=The secret of consciousness, with Daniel C. Dennett {{!}} New Philosopher|website=www.newphilosopher.com|language=en|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Other academic programs==\n\n===Summer school===\nEach summer, Phillips Exeter hosts over 780 students from various schools for a five-week program of academic study.  The summer program accommodates a diverse student body typically derived from over 40 different states and 45 foreign countries.<ref>{{cite web| last=The Trustees of Phillips Exeter Academy| title=Phillips Exeter Academy {{!}} Summer School| url=http://www.exeter.edu/summer_programs/7324.aspx| accessdate=January 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\nExeter's summer school is divided into two programs of study: Upper School, which offers a wide variety of classes to students currently enrolled in high school who are entering grades ten through 12 as well as serving postgraduates; and Access Exeter, a program for students entering grades eight and nine, which offers accelerated study in the arts, sciences and writing as well as serving as an introduction to the school itself. Access Exeter curriculum consists of six academic clusters; each cluster consists of three courses organized around a focused central theme. Some of Exeter's summer school programs also give students the opportunity to experience studies outside of Exeter's campus environment, including interactions with other top schools and students, experience with Washington D.C., and travel abroad.<ref>{{cite web|last=The Trustees of Phillips Exeter Academy|title=Phillips Exeter Academy {{!}} Academic Programs|url=http://www.exeter.edu/summer_programs/7324_7416.aspx|accessdate=January 7, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116051529/http://www.exeter.edu/summer_programs/7324_7416.aspx|archivedate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Workshops===\nThe academy offers a number of workshops and conferences for secondary school educators. These include the Exeter Math Institute; the Exeter Humanities Institute; the Math, Science and Technology Conference; the Exeter Astronomy Conference; and the Shakespeare Conference.<ref>{{cite web|title=Summer Programs |url=http://www.exeter.edu/summer_programs/88.aspx |accessdate=November 12, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220074005/http://www.exeter.edu/summer_programs/88.aspx |archivedate=December 20, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe \"On Beyond Exeter\" program offers one-week seminars for alumni. Most courses are held at the academy, but some meet in the locations central to the course's topic.\n\n===Historical endeavors===\nIn 1952, Exeter, [[Phillips Academy|Andover]], [[Lawrenceville School|Lawrenceville]], [[Harvard University|Harvard]], [[Princeton University|Princeton]] and [[Yale University|Yale]] published the study ''General Education in School and College: A Committee Report''. The report recommended examinations that would place students after admission to college. This program evolved into the [[Advanced Placement Program]].<ref>{{cite web| title = The Liberal Arts in School and College| author=Stanley N. Katz| url=http://chronicle.com/free/v52/i27/27b04601.htm|website=Chronicle.com| accessdate = November 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title = A Brief History of the Advanced Placement Program| url = http://www.collegeboard.com/prod_downloads/about/news_info/ap/ap_history_english.pdf| website = Collegeboard.com| accessdate = November 12, 2017| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090205075824/http://www.collegeboard.com/prod_downloads/about/news_info/ap/ap_history_english.pdf| archive-date = February 5, 2009| url-status = dead| df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1965 Exeter became the second charter member (after [[Phillips Academy|Andover]]) of the [[School Year Abroad]] program.<ref>{{cite web| title = A Brief History: Where did we come from?| url = http://www.sya.org/pages/sitepage.cfm?id=22&pagename=A%20Brief%20History%20of%20SYA| website = Sya.org| accessdate = November 12, 2017| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090728204959/http://www.sya.org/pages/sitepage.cfm?id=22&pagename=A%20Brief%20History%20of%20SYA| archivedate = July 28, 2009| df = mdy-all}}</ref> The program allows students to reside and study a foreign language abroad.\n\n==In popular culture==\n{{See also|List of Phillips Exeter Academy people#In fiction}}\n\nSeveral works are based on Exeter and portray the lives of its students. Many are written by alumni who disguise Exeter's name, but not its character, such as [[John Knowles]] and his novel ''[[A Separate Peace]].''\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Schools}}\n*[[Exeter point]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{citation |editor=[[Paul Monroe]] |via=HathiTrust |title= Cyclopedia of Education |publisher=Macmillan |location=New York |year=1913 |chapter=Phillips Academy, Exeter, N.H. |volume=4 |hdl=2027/uc2.ark:/13960/t1vd73q7n }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Americana Poster|Phillips (Exeter) Academy}}\n* [http://www.exeter.edu/ Phillips Exeter Academy]\n* [http://www.exetercrew.com/ Phillips Exeter Academy Crew]\n* [https://archive.is/20130209041828/http://www.webofstories.com/people/donald.hall/13 Donald Hall talking about Phillips Exeter Academy] (video)\n{{Phillips Exeter Academy}}\n\n{{Eight Schools Association}}\n{{The Ten Schools Admissions Organization}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Phillips Exeter Academy]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Private high schools in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Preparatory schools in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 1780s]]\n[[Category:1781 establishments in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Co-educational boarding schools]]\n[[Category:Schools in Rockingham County, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Exeter, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Six Schools League]]\n[[Category:Phillips family (New England)]]\n", "name_user": "Dianathemath", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable faculty:changed \"former Olympic athlete\" to \"Olympic athlete\" in two cases -- there is no such thing as a \"former Olympian.\" Once an Olympian, always an Olympian. Look it up.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phillips_Exeter_Academy"}
